<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>Cargo Management API</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/css/app.css" />
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/static/css/bootstrap.min.css" />
    <script src="/static/js/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
    <script src="/static/js/bootstrap.min.js"></script>
</head>

<body>
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-2"></div>
            <div id="Header-Text" class="col-8">
                <h1>Cargo Management API <br />-Login-</h1>
                <h5 class="text-muted">By Paul Newling</h5>
            </div>
            <div class="col-2"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-2"></div>

            <div id="Body-Text" class="col-8">
                <p>This simple web app is the portfolio project for Oregon State University's CS493 Cloud Computing.</p>
                <p>
                    Logging in with your Gmail will generate a JWT to allow you to then make backend requests to
                    <b> create, read, update, delete, boats and cargo as well as create associations between them</b> in
                    the associated datastore. After your
                    first login your unique userID will also be added to the users datastore.
                </p>
                <p>
                    To make the associated requests and interact with the backend you will need to use a tool like
                    Postman. Example
                    postman tests, the full documentation, and project code can be found on the project Github <b><a
                        href="https://github.com/PaulNewling/cargo-api" class="text-decoration-none">HERE</a></b>.
                </p>
                <form action="/authenticate" method="get">
                    <button type="submit" class="btn btn-secondary">Generate JWT</button>
                </form>
            </div>
            <div class="col-2"></div>
        </div>
</body>

</html>